body:
In the code snippet here:

``` rust
struct Foo<'a,'b,'c> { p: &'a &'b &'c () }

// *Deliberately* mismatching lifetimes on the arguments here
fn bar<'a,'b,'c,'d>(x: &mut Foo<'a,'b,'c>, y: Foo<'b,'c,'d>) {
    x.p = y.p;
}

fn main() {
    let a0 =  (); let a1 =  ();
    let b0 = &a0; let b1 = &a1;
    let c0 = &b0; let c1 = &b1;
    let d0 = &c0; let d1 = &c1;
    let mut f = Foo{ p: d0 };
    let g = Foo{ p: d1 };
    bar(&mut f, g);
}
```

When compiling the above code, we get three distinct errors about mismatched types, all highlighting the same span (the use of `y.p` in the assignment `x.p = y.p;`), as transcribed here:

```
% ./x86_64-apple-darwin/stage2/bin/rustc /tmp/k.rs && ./k
/tmp/k.rs:6:1: 8:2 note: consider using an explicit lifetime parameter as shown: fn bar<'a, 'c>(x: &mut Foo<'a, 'a, 'a>, y: Foo<'a, 'a, 'c>)
/tmp/k.rs:6 fn bar<'a,'b,'c,'d>(x: &mut Foo<'a,'b,'c>, y: Foo<'b,'c,'d>) {
/tmp/k.rs:7     x.p = y.p;
/tmp/k.rs:8 }
/tmp/k.rs:7:11: 7:14 error: mismatched types: expected `&'a &'b &'c ()` but found `&'b &'c &'d ()` (lifetime mismatch)
/tmp/k.rs:7     x.p = y.p;
                      ^~~
/tmp/k.rs:7:11: 7:14 error: mismatched types: expected `&'a &'b &'c ()` but found `&'b &'c &'d ()` (lifetime mismatch)
/tmp/k.rs:7     x.p = y.p;
                      ^~~
/tmp/k.rs:7:11: 7:14 error: mismatched types: expected `&'a &'b &'c ()` but found `&'b &'c &'d ()` (lifetime mismatch)
/tmp/k.rs:7     x.p = y.p;
                      ^~~
error: aborting due to 3 previous errors
% 
```

I suspect there are other places where we have a similar deluge of redundancy in the error message output.

Spawned off of: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/14022/files#r14777055
